whatcontribute: I believe I would be able to bring a passion for bringing joy and justice to the world. I have experience with mediation and editing, and would enjoy working with this organization.
activism_mean: To me, activism is an inherent part of existence. I choose to be an activist by supporting brands that do not engage in animal cruelty, and by creating spaces where people feel free to engage and learn about what is happening in the world around them. I encourage others to find something they are passionate about and to something to support it, whether it be raise money for a cause, participate in a march, or even just talk to someone about their viewpoints.
why_consideractivist: I care too much to be passive about what is going on in our world. Change starts small, but can grow to move mountains. By working in my local community, I am able to start the ball rolling and provide support for those who also feel passionately about their causes. One person may not be able to do a lot on their own, but if that one person can make a difference in another's life, you never know what may happen.

whatmore_wactivist: Finding other individuals in my area and working together to bring awareness

fandoms_partof: I used to be a Doctor Who fan, but I mostly identify with Harry Potter. I grew up with the books and have an emotional investment in that universe.

activism_mean: Working to bring awareness and change to social issues in our world. I usually associate activism with politics - Working to change laws, ideas, and policies for the better. But it's as important to help change attitudes and beliefs of family, friends, co-workers, etc.
consider_wactivist_4_TEXT: Yes and no. I love the idea, but most of my activism takes place outside of the HPA
why_consideractivist: I'm a privileged, white, upper-middle class, cisgender, heterosexual woman. I've had an easy life. But I've always felt compassion and empathy for those who haven't. When I was really little I wanted to befriend the kids who looked lonely, bullied, or without friends. In high school I helped co-found a chapter of STAND (Students Taking Action Now: Darfur) to raise awareness and funds to stop the genocide taking place in Darfur, Sudan. I continued working with STAND chapters throughout college. I participated in Christian missions trips, volunteered in the community, joined the board of a local youth suicide prevention non-profit (and became their artistic director) and now I work full-time for a sexual violence prevention nonprofit. It's always been an integral part of who I am to try and help those around me, in the best way I can. I'm introverted so I don't network a lot, I don't give public speeches or organize events. But I love using graphic design to help organizations create a brand, have a professional image, reach their audiences, and raise funds for the important work they do.
whatmore_wactivist: Probably being more involved specifically with the HPA. Or at least joining a local chapter! I don't think there is one in my area and I don't have the personality to start one.
whystay_hpa: My love for harry potter and for activism. I identify very strongly with both.
howlearn_hpa_TEXT: I honestly do not remember. It was around 2007. I read a lot of HP fanfiction and the movies were still being released, so it had to be something related to that.
hpa_moreof: I would to have more things like Accio Books and the Boycott of the chocolate frogs (where there are clear and practical ways to participate). The campaigns that are mostly awareness are great, but I feel like I talk so much about different issues that the people around me start to tune me out. I'd love to have more concrete actions I can take to participate other than education awareness and donations.
hpa_intweet: Fandom activists
whyno_merch: I almost bought the "books turn muggles into wizards" tank, but it sold out. I have too many regular t-shirts and coffee mugs to buy more.
merch_wanttosee: tank tops! I'd love more products with "Books turn muggles into wizards" slogan. It's my favorite.

college_degreemajor: Bachelor of Arts in English and French and Francophone Studies
ingradschool_major: English language literature (focus on Early American lit through 19th century)
fandoms_partof: Buffy the Vampire Slayer, Veronica Mars, Gilmore Girls, Lord of the Rings? I’m not a big online discussion person, but if I was it would be those. Also Octavia Butler and other American writers, but that’s usually in a quasi-adamedic context.
books_longingly: Elaine Scarry’s On Beauty and Being Just
netflix_shows: Besides The Handmaid’s Tale last summer, most of the things I binge watch on Netflix these days are things I enjoy out of nostalgia, like Gilmore Girls or Friends. To varying degrees, they’re actually things I’d rather not support through merchandise/engage on a deeper level unless it involved discussing how problematic their “humor” often is - they simply provide a good mindless retreat from grad school because I loved them when I was younger.
fandom_events_16_TEXT: Harry Potter and the Sacred Text Weekly Discussion Group in Cambridge
fandom_events_17_TEXT: Harry Potter and the Sacred Text Live Podcast Event in Somerville
whatcontribute: I have great communication and critical thinking skills (I’m working on a PhD in English at Harvard!), valuable contacts in higher education, and lots of research experience - creative search terms and resourcefulness ftw! I’m also both passionate and compassionate.
activism_mean: Activism means engaging with the world in a way that might improve the material conditions of someone’s existence. This engagement could happen in any number of ways - an activist should play to their strengths! The HPA is wonderful because it allows fans to take what they already know and love and turn it into love for the rest of the world.
why_consideractivist: One of the skills I have practiced the most is writing, so I write to my representatives whenever I can about human rights and environmental justice issues. I also call them when it feels more appropriate! Communicating with my representatives gives them the tools to create legislation that reflects the opinions of at least one more constituent. /  / Whenever I can, I also try to turn my access to elite higher education back to people who do not have that access. I’ve had a lot of opportunities to think about social justice that not everyone I interact with has had. By gently calling people into conversations I’ve been thinking about for a while, I hope to expand a little at a time the circle of citizens thinking about social justice. Hopefully some of them will in turn do the same! I truly believe that open conversation and awareness are how we get to more socially just politics and, in turn, legislation.
feel_wactivist: Harry Potter has shaped the way I see the world. By treating the text with rigor each week in my Harry Potter as a Sacred Text discussion group, having faith that it has endless lessons to impart and that we can find these lessons in community, I treat Harry Potter as a sort of engine that can always help me think about the energy and assumptions I am bringing to the world.
whatmore_wactivist: I would love to be more involved in the HPA! I tried to start a chapter at my undergrad institution several years back, but my co-organizer transferred away from the school and it never got off the ground. I think the organization is amazing, and I still want to be an active part of it.
whystay_hpa: There is so much power in community activism.
areas_of_activism_12_TEXT: But actually, can I check off all of them?
hpa_moreof: Critical discussion of responsible fandom - what does it mean to use a text to inspire activism when that text also, for example, performs the metaphorical elision of real Black experience and white poverty in a fictional landscape like Panem?
hpa_lessof: Using volunteer labor. Don’t get me wrong, I understand that it’s a non-profit and that one of the amazing things about the organization is that it consolidates and directs fan energy! But maybe there’s a way for those who want to work for the HPA but financially can’t afford the volunteer hours to make some inroads without sacrificing needed work hours? I am not personally in this situation but know plenty of people can’t dedicate ten+ free hours a week. That doesn’t mean they’re not fans who might want to be involved!
hpa_intweet: When you think of the news exclusively in metaphors from your favorite stories...there’s an alliance for that ⚡️⚖️📚
whatimprove: Perhaps regularly post some more direct ways folks who do not belong to a chapter (often for geographical reasons) can participate. Virtual chapters/virtual involvement in existing chapters?
merch_wanttosee: Anything fair trade, lots of intersectional feminist logos!
